Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: The core challenge in model pruning—especially for large and complex models like Transformers—is balancing compression efficiency with performance preservation. Existing methods often focus on identifying unimportant weights or channels, but they typically reconstruct *all* features post-pruning, regardless of whether those features will be retained in subsequent layers or stages. This leads to wasted computation and suboptimal resource allocation. Inspired by Paper 2’s insight that some reconstructed features are later pruned (and thus their reconstruction is redundant), I extend this reasoning into a dynamic, forward-looking framework. Unlike prior work that uses static importance scores or local layer-wise criteria, my idea introduces an adaptive, cross-layer feature importance propagation mechanism that predicts which features will be deemed unimportant in future pruning stages. By integrating this predictive importance map with a suppression policy during reconstruction, we avoid computationally expensive and unnecessary recovery of features destined for removal. Furthermore, while Paper 1 leverages output fluctuation for structured pruning and Paper 3 uses principled optimization, none explicitly address the inefficiency of reconstructing transient features. My approach uniquely couples **pruning trajectory forecasting** with **adaptive reconstruction suppression**, making it both novel and highly practical for retraining-free scenarios. This reduces computational overhead during pruning and improves final model fidelity by focusing resources only on persistent, high-impact features.

